Experiment II 
Objective: Creating and managing repositories on GitHub, Branching and merging. 
Required Software / Tools: GIT, GITHUB, Python, VSCode 
Procedure: 
1. Steps to Create a GitHub Account 
a. Go to GitHub Website Open your browser and visit github.com. 
b. Click “Sign up” You’ll find this option in the top-right corner of the 
homepage. 
c. Enter Your Details 
 Username: Choose a unique name (this will be visible to others). 
 Email address: Use a valid email you can access. 
 Password: Create a strong password. 
d. Verify Your Account GitHub may ask you to solve a puzzle or captcha to 
confirm you’re human. 
e. Confirm Email Check your inbox for a verification email from GitHub and 
click the link inside to activate your account. 
f. Set Up Preferences You can skip or customize settings later. 
g. Start Using GitHub Once logged in, you can create repositories, explore 
projects, and collaborate with others. 
2. Create GitHub repository, on left pane click on + icon in the top-right corner and 
select New repository. And fill the details: 
a. Repository name (must be unique under your account). 
b. Description (optional). 
c. Choose Public or Private. 
d. Check Add a README file if you want a starter file. 
e. Click Create repository. 
3. Set up local Working directory and terminal for Experiment 2: 
a. Open Visual Studio > Menu options > File > Open Folder > Right click > 
create New Folder with name Exp2. 
b. Open Visual studio > Menu options > Terminal > New Terminal. 
4. From the terminal run below commands to initialize git in the Exp2 folder.  
git init 
git status 
5. Create a file, on VSCode left pane click + New file and name it num.py. On right 
pane write a basic Python program as below: 
# Print numbers (without input) 
n = 10  # fixed value 
for i in range(1, n + 1): 
print(i) 
6. Save the file and move to git Stage and commit the file using below commands: 
git add num.py 
git commit -m " num.py code without inputs" 
7. Integrate GIT to GitHub: 
a. Create client keys by running below command on Git terminal :  
ssh-keygen -o 
b. Let the value be default for key location and let passphrase be empty. (Hit 
Enter to generate keys). 
c. Now look for line “Your public key has been saved in ..” in above output. 
d. Copy the contents of public key using below command: 
cat C:\Users\Lenovo/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub 
e. Now update public key in GitHub: 
 Go to GitHub > Top Right > User Navigator Menu > Settings 
 On settings Left Pane > Click SSH and GPG Keys 
 Top Right > Click New SSH Key 
 Updated Title as Clientkey1 and in key paste value copied from GIT. 
 Click Add SSH Key to finish the GIT and GitHub integration.  
8. Now got to GitHub and click on your repo. 
9. Copy below commands from GitHub and run-on Git terminal to push code to 
GitHub repository.  
NOTE: Copy commands from your GitHub repo, below commands for reference. 
git branch -M main 
git remote add origin https://github.com/bandarichandra510/Exp2.git 
git push -u origin main 
10. Now refresh GitHub and you must see numpy file under Exp2 repository.  
 
 
 
 
11. Now create a new branch with name dev using below command in Git Terminal: 
 
git switch -c dev 
 
git branch 
 
NOTE: git branch is command that lists all branches and * indicates on which 
branch you are working on. 
 
 
 
 
12. Now create a new file in visual studio with name num1.py and update below code. 
 
 
 
 
13. Add and commit the num1.py file in GIT. 
 
git add num1.py 
 
git commit -m " num1.py code with inputs" 
 
git status 
 
 
 
 
 
14. Now switch to main branch using below commands: 
 
git branch 
git switch main 
git branch 
 
NOTE: As you switch from dev to main branch you can see num1.py is strike 
since the num1.py was commit on dev branch and now we you switched to main.  
 
 
 
15. Now merge dev branch to main branch using below command: 
 
git merge dev 
 
NOTE: Now you see strike out line on num1.py goes off automatically. 
 
 
 
16. Now push the num1.py code to GitHub using below command : 
 
git push -u origin main 
 
 
 
 
